{"name": "ejpcsvparser", "metadata": {"name": "ejpcsvparser", "version": "0.4.0", "classifiers": ["Development Status :: 3 - Alpha", "Intended Audience :: Developers", "License :: OSI Approved :: MIT License", "Programming Language :: Python :: 3", "Programming Language :: Python :: 3.5"], "home_page": "https://github.com/elifesciences/ejp-csv-parser", "license": "MIT", "documentation_url": null, "dependencies": ["elifearticle", "elifetools", "GitPython", "configparser"], "summary": "EJP CSV parser for building article objects.", "upload_time": 1728082378}, "documentation": ["# ejp-csv-parser\n\nEJP CSV parser for building article objects.\n\nThis library reads CSV files containing article manuscript data, creates objects defined in the `elifearticle` library, and sets object properties from the CSV data values.\n\nCurrently it reads CSV files for data including: title, abstract, DOI, editor, authors, group authors, license, received date, subjects, keywords, research organisms, datasets, funding, and ethics.\n\nThe `settings.py` module defines file names, column names, angle bracket escape sequence, folder names, and similar settings which can be adjusted slightly if required.\n\nThe `parse.py` module is a good starting place to invoke the library, if given an article ID value, it can read the CSV files for data, create objects and set their properties for that particular article.\n\nThe `csv_data.py` module contains the logic for reading the CSV files, linking rows from multiple files by their index columns, escaping and converting some character encoding, and accounting for comma characters that are not intende to delimit data fields.\n\nThe objects instantiated by this library are used to generate a JATS XML file for a Publish on Accept (PoA) research article.\n\n## Requirements and install\n\na) Install from `pypi` package index\n\n```\npip install ejpcsvparser\n```\n\nb) Install locally\n\nClone the git repo\n\n`git clone https://github.com/elifesciences/ejp-csv-parser.git`\n\nCreate a python virtual environment and activate it\n\n```\npython3 -m venv venv\nsource venv/bin/activate\n```\n\nInstall it locally\n\n```\npip install -r requirements.txt\npython setup.py install\n```\n\nIn order to run the transform function as written, it will require `strip-coverletter` to be installed and ready to run locally, which will also require `Docker` to be installed and running.\n\n## Example usage\n\nThis library is meant to be integrated into another operational system, where the CSV files are downloaded from an S3 bucket and then processed. The test scenarios may provide more details about how it could be invoked, and the following example is a simple way to see how it works using interactive Python and using files from the `\"tests/test_data/\"` folder as the CSV input:\n\n```python\n>>> from ejpcsvparser import parse\n>>> article, error_count, error_messages = parse.build_article(21598)\n>>> print(article.doi)\n10.7554/eLife.21598\n>>> print(article.title)\nCryo-EM structures of the autoinhibited <italic>E. coli</italic> ATP synthase in three rotational states\n```\n\n## Run code tests\n\nUse `pytest` for testing, install it if missing:\n\n```\npip install pytest\n```\n\nRun tests\n\n```\npytest\n```\n\nRun tests with `coverage` (install it if missing):\n\n```\ncoverage run -m pytest\n```\n\nthen report on code coverage\n\n```\ncoverage report -m\n```\n\n## License\n\nLicensed under [MIT](https://opensource.org/licenses/mit-license.php).\n"], "modules": [{"name": "ejpcsvparser", "documentation": [], "functions": [{"name": "ejpcsvparser.configure_logging", "asynchronous": false, "params": [{"name": "filename", "type": null, "default": null}, {"name": "level", "type": null, "default": "..."}, {"name": "format_string", "type": null, "default": "..."}], "returns": null, "documentation": []}], "variables": [{"name": "ejpcsvparser.__version__", "type": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "ejpcsvparser.LOGGER", "type": null, "documentation": []}], "classes": [], "exports": []}, {"name": "ejpcsvparser.settings", "documentation": ["csv reading settings"], "functions": [], "variables": [{"name": "ejpcsvparser.settings.ROWS_WITH_COLNAMES", "type": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "ejpcsvparser.settings.DATA_START_ROW", "type": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "ejpcsvparser.settings.LESS_THAN_ESCAPE_SEQUENCE", "type": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "ejpcsvparser.settings.GREATER_THAN_ESCAPE_SEQUENCE", "type": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "ejpcsvparser.settings.CSV_PATH", "type": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "ejpcsvparser.settings.TMP_DIR", "type": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "ejpcsvparser.settings.CSV_FILES", "type": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "ejpcsvparser.settings.OVERFLOW_CSV_FILES", "type": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "ejpcsvparser.settings.CSV_COLUMN_HEADINGS", "type": null, "documentation": []}], "classes": [], "exports": []}, {"name": "ejpcsvparser.utils", "documentation": [], "functions": [{"name": "ejpcsvparser.utils.allowed_tags", "asynchronous": false, "params": [], "returns": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "ejpcsvparser.utils.article_type_indexes", "asynchronous": false, "params": [], "returns": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "ejpcsvparser.utils.entity_to_unicode", "asynchronous": false, "params": [{"name": "string", "type": null, "default": null}], "returns": null, "documentation": ["Quick convert unicode HTML entities to unicode characters\nusing a regular expression replacement"]}, {"name": "ejpcsvparser.utils.entities", "asynchronous": false, "params": [{"name": "function", "type": null, "default": null}], "returns": null, "documentation": ["Convert entities to unicode as a decorator"]}, {"name": "ejpcsvparser.utils.decode_brackets", "asynchronous": false, "params": [{"name": "string", "type": null, "default": null}], "returns": null, "documentation": ["Decode angle bracket escape sequence\nused to encode XML content"]}, {"name": "ejpcsvparser.utils.unserialise_angle_brackets", "asynchronous": false, "params": [{"name": "escaped_string", "type": null, "default": null}], "returns": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "ejpcsvparser.utils.convert_to_xml_string", "asynchronous": false, "params": [{"name": "string", "type": null, "default": null}], "returns": null, "documentation": ["For input strings with escaped tags and special characters\nissue a set of conversion functions to prepare it prior\nto adding it to an article object"]}, {"name": "ejpcsvparser.utils.escape_angle_brackets", "asynchronous": false, "params": [{"name": "string", "type": null, "default": null}], "returns": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "ejpcsvparser.utils.get_elife_doi", "asynchronous": false, "params": [{"name": "article_id", "type": null, "default": null}], "returns": null, "documentation": ["Given an article_id, return a DOI for the eLife journal"]}, {"name": "ejpcsvparser.utils.decode_cp1252", "asynchronous": false, "params": [{"name": "string", "type": null, "default": null}], "returns": null, "documentation": ["CSV files look to be in CP-1252 encoding (Western Europe)\nDecoding to ASCII is normally fine, except when it gets an O umlaut, for example\nIn this case, values must be decoded from cp1252 in order to be added as unicode\nto the final XML output.\nThis function helps do that in selected places, like on author surnames"]}, {"name": "ejpcsvparser.utils.clean_funder", "asynchronous": false, "params": [{"name": "funder", "type": null, "default": null}], "returns": null, "documentation": ["Remove extra content from funder names\nseparated by | character\nand anything in parentheses"]}], "variables": [], "classes": [], "exports": []}, {"name": "ejpcsvparser.csv_data", "documentation": [], "functions": [{"name": "ejpcsvparser.csv_data.memoize", "asynchronous": false, "params": [{"name": "value", "type": null, "default": null}], "returns": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "ejpcsvparser.